"1.0.0"}],"findings":[{"description":"No aggregate cap on liability was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Absent a cap, liability is unbounded — an unusual posture for a commercial MSA.","id":"MSA-006-s1-0","recommendation":"Add an aggregate cap (commonly 12 months' fees) with explicit carve-outs.","rule_id":"MSA-006","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"critical","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-aggregate-cap","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — aggregate cap","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Aggregate liability cap missing"},{"description":"No third-party IP infringement indemnification clause was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"A vendor-supplied product that infringes a third party's IP exposes the customer to suit. The standard allocation is that the vendor indemnifies for IP claims.","id":"MSA-001-s1-0","recommendation":"Add a third-party IP infringement indemnity (defense, settlement, damages) with the usual customer-cooperation conditions.","rule_id":"MSA-001","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-indemnification-scope","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — indemnification scope","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"IP infringement indemnity missing"},{"description":"No background / foreground IP ownership clause was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Without allocation, default copyright / patent rules govern, which rarely matches the parties' intent.","id":"MSA-011-s1-0","recommendation":"Add explicit allocation: each party retains its background IP; foreground IP ownership rule (usually customer for deliverables, vendor for tooling).","rule_id":"MSA-011","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-ip-allocation","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — IP allocation","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Background / foreground IP allocation missing"},{"description":"No compliance-with-laws or non-infringement warranty was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Customers expect a vendor to warrant lawful operation and non-infringement.","id":"MSA-014-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: services and deliverables (a) comply with applicable laws and (b) do not infringe any third-party IP rights.","rule_id":"MSA-014","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-compliance-non-infringement","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — compliance/non-infringement","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Compliance-with-laws / non-infringement warranty missing"},{"description":"No SLA / service level agreement / uptime commitment was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"An MSA for hosted services without an SLA leaves availability promises unenforceable.","id":"MSA-016-s1-0","recommendation":"Reference an SLA (attached or linked) with uptime, support response, and remedy schedules.","rule_id":"MSA-016","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-sla-reference","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — SLA reference","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"SLA reference missing"},{"description":"No data-return / data-portability / export-format clause was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Without an explicit return obligation the customer can be locked out of its own data.","id":"MSA-021-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: on termination, vendor shall return all customer data in a machine-readable format and then delete its copies within N days.","rule_id":"MSA-021","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-data-return","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — data return","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Data return / portability missing"},{"description":"The MSA's stated precedence places it above the SOW/Order Form, but operative terms (indemnity, liability, IP, warranty) appear in those subordinate documents.","document_position":357,"excerpt":{"end_offset":637,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":357,"text":"1. Order of Precedence. In the event of any conflict or inconsistency between this MSA and any Statement of Work (\"SOW\"), the terms of this MSA shall control and govern, except to the extent that a SOW explicitly states that it supersedes a specific provision of this MSA by refer"},"explanation":"When precedence puts the MSA on top of its SOWs, terms that actually live in a SOW may be overridden by silent MSA defaults at the moment of conflict. The order is internally inconsistent with where the operative terms sit.","id":"MSA-027-s1-357","recommendation":"Either relocate the operative term to the MSA, carve out the term from the precedence rule (e.g., 'except for the limitation of liability set out in the SOW'), or invert the precedence for that subject.","rule_id":"MSA-027","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-order-of-precedence-consistency","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-13T00:00:00Z","source":"Order-of-precedence consistency","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Order-of-precedence may bury operative terms"},{"description":"Used but not defined: Disclosing Party, One Million Dollars.","document_position":1944,"excerpt":{"end_offset":1960,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":1944,"text":"Disclosing Party"},"explanation":"Title-Case phrases in a contract usually signal a defined term. When they aren't defined, readers must guess at the intended meaning. Either define them or use lowercase if the term is intended in its ordinary sense.","id":"STRUCT-006-s1-1944","recommendation":"Add a definition for each genuinely defined term, or change the casing if the phrase is being used in its ordinary sense.","rule_id":"STRUCT-006","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Undefined Title-Case terms: 2"},{"description":"The following references do not resolve to any section: Section 8(a), Section 5, Section 7.","document_position":4818,"excerpt":{"end_offset":4830,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":4818,"text":"Section 8(a)"},"explanation":"A broken cross-reference can mean the referenced section was renumbered or deleted, or that a section reference was made up. Either way the reader has no way to follow the citation.","id":"STRUCT-007-s1-4818","recommendation":"Update each broken reference to point to the correct section, or delete it if it is no longer applicable.","rule_id":"STRUCT-007","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Unresolved cross-references: 3"},{"description":"The contract does not state what happens upon termination.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no effect-of-termination clause)"},"explanation":"An effect-of-termination clause spells out the rights and obligations that survive, the return or destruction of materials, and the wind-down rules.","id":"TERM-005-s1-0","rule_id":"TERM-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"No effect-of-termination clause detected"},{"description":"The document does not state where disputes must be brought.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no venue clause)"},"explanation":"Without a venue clause, default venue rules apply (in federal court, 28 U.S.C. § 1391). A clear forum-selection clause avoids ambiguity.","id":"CHOICE-003-s1-0","rule_id":"CHOICE-003","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"stat-28-usc-1391","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"28 U.S.C. § 1391 (venue generally)","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/28/1391"}],"title":"No venue / forum clause detected"},{"description":"No indemnification covering breach of confidentiality was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Confidentiality breaches often produce damages that are difficult to quantify; indemnification anchors the remedy.","id":"MSA-003-s1-0","recommendation":"Add an indemnity for damages arising from breach of confidentiality obligations.","rule_id":"MSA-003","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-confidentiality-indemnity","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — confidentiality indemnity","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Confidentiality breach indemnity missing"},{"description":"No termination-on-insolvency clause was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"11 U.S.C. § 365 makes pure ipso-facto clauses unenforceable in some scenarios, but the contract should still anchor the parties' intent.","id":"MSA-019-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: termination on filing for bankruptcy, appointment of receiver, or assignment for the benefit of creditors.","rule_id":"MSA-019","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-11-u-s-c-365-bankruptcy-considerations","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"11 U.S.C. § 365 — Bankruptcy considerations","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/11/365"}],"title":"Termination for bankruptcy / insolvency missing"},{"description":"No transition / wind-down / hosted-service continuation period was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Without a wind-down, the customer can be cut off mid-migration.","id":"MSA-020-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: vendor will continue providing the service for up to N (e.g., 90) days post-termination at then-current rates to facilitate transition.","rule_id":"MSA-020","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-transition-assistance","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — transition assistance","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Wind-down / transition assistance missing"},{"description":"No bilateral force-majeure language was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"A one-sided force-majeure clause (vendor-only) is commercially abnormal; payment obligations are conventionally excluded.","id":"MSA-022-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: 'neither party shall be liable for delay or failure due to force majeure', with a payment-obligation carve-out.","rule_id":"MSA-022","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-balanced-force-majeure","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — balanced force majeure","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Balanced force majeure missing"},{"description":"No amendment-in-writing or no-waiver boilerplate found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Without these, oral modifications and unintentional waivers become litigation risks.","id":"MSA-025-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: 'no amendment is effective unless in writing signed by both parties' and 'no failure to enforce shall be deemed a waiver.'","rule_id":"MSA-025","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-amendment-waiver","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — amendment / waiver","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Amendment-in-writing / no-waiver missing"},{"description":"No survival or entire-agreement / integration clause was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Without survival, sticky obligations (confidentiality, IP, indemnity) may not outlive termination. Without integration, prior negotiations may be admissible.","id":"MSA-026-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: a survival clause enumerating sticky obligations and an entire-agreement clause superseding prior negotiations.","rule_id":"MSA-026","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-commercial-drafting-baseline-survival-entire-agreement","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"Commercial drafting baseline — survival / entire agreement","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc"}],"title":"Survival / entire-agreement clause missing"},{"description":"No clause was found addressing AI / generative AI usage by the vendor in service delivery.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"Increasingly the contract should disclose AI use, training data, and IP ownership of outputs (see the §49 AI Addendum playbook for the deep check).","id":"MSA-028-s1-0","recommendation":"Add a clause disclosing whether AI is used, naming material AI subprocessors, and addressing IP in outputs.","rule_id":"MSA-028","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-nist-ai-rmf-transparency-baseline","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"NIST AI RMF — transparency baseline","source_url":"https://www.nist.gov/itl/ai-risk-management-framework"}],"title":"AI usage clause missing"},{"description":"Exclusive / limited remedy language is present but no UCC § 2-719(2) fail-of-essential-purpose escape was found.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(clause absent from the document)"},"explanation":"UCC § 2-719(2) preserves alternative remedies when a limited remedy fails of its essential purpose — anchoring this protects the customer from a remedy gap.","id":"MSA-030-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: 'if the limited remedy is found to fail of its essential purpose, the customer's other remedies under this Agreement and applicable law remain available.'","rule_id":"MSA-030","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[{"id":"msa-deep-u-c-c-2-719-2-","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"U.C.C. § 2-719(2)","source_url":"https://www.law.cornell.edu/ucc/2/2-719"}],"title":"UCC § 2-719 limited-remedy escape missing"},{"description":"The indemnifying party shall not settle any claim in a manner that imposes liability on the indemnified party without th | EACH PARTY'S AGGREGATE LIABILITY TO THE OTHER PARTY FOR ALL CLAIMS ARISING OUT OF OR RELATED TO THIS AGREEMENT SHALL NOT | The aggregate liability cap in Section 8(a) shall not apply to: (i) either party's breach of its confidentiality obligat | THIS MUTUAL EXCLUSION OF CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES SHALL NOT APPLY TO BREACHES OF CONFIDENTIALITY OR INDEMNIFICATION OBLIGAT","document_position":4309,"excerpt":{"end_offset":4474,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":4309,"text":"The indemnifying party shall not settle any claim in a manner that imposes liability on the indemnified party without the indemnified party's prior written consent."},"explanation":"Negative covenants restrict what a party may do. Surfacing them collectively makes it easier to check they are intended and consistent with the overall deal.","id":"OBLI-005-s1-4309","rule_id":"OBLI-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Negative covenants: 4"},{"description":"INCIDENTAL, SPECIAL, EXEMPLARY, OR CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES","document_position":5199,"excerpt":{"end_offset":5255,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":5199,"text":"8. Limitation of Liability. (a) Aggregate Liability Cap. EACH PARTY'S AGGREGATE LIABILITY TO THE OTHER PARTY FOR ALL CLAIMS ARISING OUT OF OR RELATED TO THIS AGREEMENT SHALL NOT EXCEED THE TOTAL FEES PAID OR PAYABLE BY CUSTOMER TO VENDOR IN"},"explanation":"A waiver of consequential, special, incidental, and punitive damages is standard in commercial contracts. The waiver should be mutual unless deliberately asymmetric.","id":"RISK-007-s1-5199","rule_id":"RISK-007","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Consequential damages waiver present"},{"description":"commercial general liability insurance with limits of at least One Million Dollars ($1,000,000","document_position":5721,"excerpt":{"end_offset":5815,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":5721,"text":"9. Insurance. During the term of this Agreement, Vendor shall maintain at its own expense: (a) commercial general liability insurance with limits of at least One Million Dollars ($1,000,000) per occurrence and Two Million Dollars ($2,000,000) in the aggregate; (b) professional liability / errors and omissions insurance"},"explanation":"Insurance levels should match the deal size and risk. Common minimums are $1M per occurrence CGL and $2M E&O for services contracts.","id":"RISK-010-s1-5721","rule_id":"RISK-010","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Insurance requirements stated"},{"description":"Indemnity clause appears to be missing: notice, defense control, settlement consent.","document_position":3161,"excerpt":{"end_offset":3169,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":3161,"text":"7. Mutual Indemnification. (a) Vendor Indemnification. Vendor shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless Customer and its officers, directors, employees, and agents from and against any third-party claim, action, or proceeding arising out of or relating to any allegation that the"},"explanation":"A complete indemnity clause specifies (a) the timeline and form for notice of a claim, (b) which party controls defense, and (c) whether settlement requires consent.","id":"RISK-011-s1-3161","rule_id":"RISK-011","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Indemnity procedural elements missing: notice, defense control, settlement consent"},{"description":"Vaulytica did not find a Definitions section or any inline-defined terms.","document_position":0,"excerpt":{"end_offset":0,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":0,"text":"(no definitions located)"},"explanation":"Most non-trivial contracts capitalize defined terms and either set them out in a Definitions section or define them inline (\"X\" means …). Their absence is not by itself a problem, but downstream rules that check for use of specific defined terms will be skipped.","id":"STRUCT-004-s1-0","rule_id":"STRUCT-004","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"No defined terms detected"}],"playbook_id":"msa-vendor-deep","playbook_match_confidence":1,"playbook_match_reasoning":"forced via sidecar to msa-vendor-deep","result_hash":"6ceb1e346322273ba2e09c337d27683661e6d16f2146e01e5465f096ad42392e","source_file":{"name":"msa-vendor-deep-missing-survival-entire-agreement-fail.txt","sha256":"48ca292a40a2bcbac8c3ed8aec1da8cb8968bac3d73907adfe8c93c8ad2be921","size_bytes":1},"version":"9.41.0"}